INTRODUCTION
Welcome to your Full Body S.I.T. Workout Guide!
This ebook is designed to be the perfect companion to our follow-along workout video, giving you everything you need to understand and master Sprint Interval Training (S.I.T.) right from your living room.
With just 20 minutes a day, you’ll boost your metabolism, strengthen your muscles, and improve your cardiovascular health—all with exercises you can easily do at home, no gym required!
Whether you’re new to S.I.T. or looking for a structured program that fits your busy schedule, this guide pairs with our video for a complete, step-by-step workout experience. Let’s get ready to crush those fitness goals together!
1
BENEFITS OF S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT
What is S.I.T. Training (Sprint Interval Training)?
Most likely, you already know all about S.I.T workouts, any why they are so great - after all that’s how you got here! But if you need a refresher, no worries! Sprint Interval Training (S.I.T.) is a game-changer, especially for women 40 and older. Unlike traditional cardio which requires you to grind away for long periods, S.I.T. is all about short, intense bursts of activity followed by lower-intensity recovery. It's fast and efficient, and the benefits are impressive.
Here’s the kicker: S.I.T. has been shown to boost metabolism, improve cardiovascular health, and torch fat faster than your typical workout. For women in their 40s, this kind of training helps to combat age-related muscle loss, supports joint health, and makes the most of your workout time—because let’s be real, life’s busy! You can get your heart racing, feel energized, and walk away with a big sense of accomplishment in just 7 minutes. Sounds like a win-win, right?
This Ebook is a follow-along guide for your Bonus S.I.T workout, and is meant to help provide you with some extra insight and information so you can make the most of your routine!
2
WHAT YOU NEED FOR THIS WORKOUT
Note that this workout is longer than the traditional 7- minute workouts that you might find in the One & Done program, that’s because this is specially designed to push you a little harder! If you aren’t able to complete the intermediate/advanced workouts in the traditional One & Done Program, then I would suggest you start there before starting this!
If you’re ready to start then follow these steps! Get your video loaded on any smart device, whether your phone, iPad, or smart TV! Then all you’ll need is:
Water Yoga mat A watch or timer Light weights (if applicable)
3
20-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (NO WEIGHTS)
Warm-Up (3 Minutes) Let's start by getting your body ready. Warm up with these movements to get your blood flowing and your muscles prepared:
EXERCISE REPS
March in Place 30 seconds
30 seconds forward, Arm Circles 30 seconds backward
Bodyweight Squats 30 seconds
30 seconds clockwise, 30 Hip Circles seconds counterclockwise
Now, let's jump into the intervals!
4
20-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (NO WEIGHTS)
Main Workout (16 Minutes) This S.I.T. workout alternates between 30-second all-out effort and 60-second active recovery. We'll do 4 rounds of the following 4 exercises:
EXERCISE REPS
High Knees Active Recovery: march in place (60 sec)
30 seconds all-out sprint
30 seconds, jump as Jump Squats Active Recovery: air squats (60 sec) high as you can
Mountain Climbers Active Recovery: standing toe touches (60 sec) Burpees Active Recovery: walk in place or step side to side (60 sec)
30 seconds, fast pace
30 seconds, as many as you can
Repeat the circuit 4 times.
*BURPEE MODIFICATION: If you have trouble doing burpees - you can do squat step backs! see the exercise list at the back for instructions!
5
20-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (NO WEIGHTS)
Cool-Down (1 Minute) Slow things down to help your body recover:
EXERCISE REPS Standing Hamstring 30 seconds Stretch
Quad Stretch 30 seconds
6
20-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (LIGHT WEIGHTS)
Warm-Up (3 Minutes) Gently warm up with these moves before grabbing your weights:
EXERCISE REPS
Arm Swings 30 seconds
30 seconds Bodyweight Lunges
30 seconds each Hip Circles direction
30 seconds forward, 30 Shoulder rolls seconds backward
7
20-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (LIGHT WEIGHTS)
Main Workout (16 Minutes) You’ll need a set of light dumbbells (2-5 lbs). Do 30-second intense intervals followed by 60-second active recovery. Repeat 4 rounds of the following:
EXERCISE REPS hold dumbbells, Weighted Punches Active Recovery: shoulder rolls (60 sec) fast-paced jabs Kettlebell Swings with mimic the motion with Dumbbells your weights Active Recovery: air squats (60 sec) Weighted Step Jacks hold dumbbells and step side-to- Active Recovery: slow side steps side, raising weights overhead without weights (60 sec) Dumbbell Thrusters squat and press weights Active Recovery: standing side overhead stretches (60 sec)
Repeat the circuit 4 times.
8
20-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (LIGHT WEIGHTS)
Cool-Down (1 Minute) Let’s wind down with these stretches:
EXERCISE REPS
Overhead Reach Stretch 30 seconds
Seated Hamstring 30 seconds Stretch
9
10-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (NO WEIGHTS)
Warm-Up (1 Minute) Start by getting your muscles ready for action with this quick warm-up:
EXERCISE REPS
March in Place 30 seconds
15 seconds forward, Arm Circles 15 seconds backward
10
10-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (NO WEIGHTS)
Main Workout (8 Minutes) This S.I.T. workout alternates between 30-second intense intervals and 30-second active recovery. You'll complete 2 rounds of the following exercises:
EXERCISE REPS
High Knees Active Recovery: march in place (30 sec)
30 seconds all-out sprint
30 seconds, jump as high as you can
Jump Squats Active Recovery: air squats (30 sec)
Mountain Climbers Active Recovery: standing toe touches (30 sec) Burpees Active Recovery: walk in place or step side to side (30 sec)
30 seconds, fast pace
30 seconds, as many as you can
Repeat the circuit once for a total of 2 rounds.
11
10-MINUTE S.I.T. STYLE WORKOUT (NO WEIGHTS)
Cool-Down (1 Minute) Let’s wind down with these stretches:
EXERCISE REPS Standing hamstring 30 seconds stretch
Child’s Pose 30 seconds
And there you have it! A fast, effective workout that’ll get your heart pumping and muscles moving, all in just 10 minutes.
12
INSTRUCTIONS FOR EACH EXERCISE
WARM-UP (3 MINUTES)
March in Place (30 seconds)
Stand tall with your arms relaxed at your sides. Begin lifting your knees one at a time as if you are marching. Swing your arms naturally in coordination with your legs. Keep a moderate pace to get your heart rate up, but don’t overexert yourself.
Arm Circles (30 seconds forward, 30 seconds backward)
Extend your arms out to the sides at shoulder height, keeping them straight. Begin making small circles with your arms, gradually increasing the size of the circles. For the first 30 seconds, rotate your arms forward. Then, reverse the direction for the next 30 seconds, circling your arms backward.
Bodyweight Squats (30 seconds)
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and toes slightly turned out. Lower your body into a squat by pushing your hips back and bending your knees, keeping your chest lifted and your weight in your heels. Return to standing by pressing through your heels and squeezing your glutes at the top. Repeat at a steady pace.
Hip Circles (30 seconds clockwise, 30 seconds counterclockwise)
Stand with your feet slightly wider than hip-width apart. Place your hands on your hips and make large, slow circles with your hips, keeping your upper body still. Rotate your hips in a clockwise direction for 30 seconds, then switch to counterclockwise for another 30 seconds.
13
INSTRUCTIONS FOR EACH EXERCISE
MAIN WORKOUT (16 MINUTES)
High Knees (30 seconds all-out sprint)
Stand with your feet hip-width apart. Begin running in place, driving your knees up as high as possible toward your chest. Pump your arms as you would when sprinting. Keep your core engaged and aim for a fast pace to raise your heart rate.
Active Recovery: March in place for 60 seconds, lifting your knees moderately high and moving at a relaxed pace.
Jump Squats (30 seconds)
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Lower into a squat position by bending your knees and pushing your hips back. Explode upward by jumping into the air, reaching your hands overhead. Land softly with your knees slightly bent, and immediately lower back into the squat position to repeat.
Active Recovery: Perform air squats for 60 seconds at a slow, controlled pace, lowering into a squat without jumping.
Mountain Climbers (30 seconds fast pace)
Start in a plank position with your hands directly under your shoulders and your body in a straight line from head to heels. Quickly alternate driving your knees toward your chest as if "climbing" in place. Keep your core tight and your hips low, moving at a fast pace.
Active Recovery: Stand up and slowly perform standing toe touches for 60 seconds. Reach down toward your toes while keeping your legs straight, alternating hands. 14
INSTRUCTIONS FOR EACH EXERCISE
MAIN WORKOUT (16 MINUTES)
Burpees (30 seconds, as many as you can)
Start standing with your feet shoulder-width apart. Drop into a squat position, place your hands on the ground, and jump your feet back into a plank position. Lower your chest to the ground in a push-up motion, then push back up. Jump your feet forward to your hands and explosively jump into the air, reaching your arms overhead. Repeat.
Active Recovery: Walk in place or step side to side for 60 seconds, moving at a slow and steady pace.
BURPEE MODIFICATION
Squat to Step Back (30 seconds, as many as you can)
Start in a standing position with feet shoulder-width apart. Perform a squat, lowering down as if sitting back into a chair. As you rise from the squat, step one leg back into a reverse lunge, keeping your torso upright. Return to standing, then repeat with the other leg. Continue alternating legs.
Active Recovery: Walk in place or step side to side for 60 seconds, moving at a slow and steady pace.
15
INSTRUCTIONS FOR EACH EXERCISE
COOL-DOWN (1 MINUTE)
Standing Hamstring Stretch (30 seconds)
Stand with your feet together and hinge forward at your hips, reaching your hands toward your toes. Keep your legs straight but avoid locking your knees. Hold this position for 30 seconds, feeling the stretch along the back of your legs.
Child’s Pose on the Floor (30 seconds)
Kneel on the floor and sit back on your heels. Lower your torso toward the ground and stretch your arms forward, resting your forehead on the floor. Hold this position for 30 seconds, focusing on deep, calming breaths.

INTRODUCTION
Welcome to your Full Body S.I.T. Workout Guide!
This ebook is designed to be the perfect companion to our follow-along workout video, giving you everything you need to understand and master Sprint Interval Training (S.I.T.) right from your living room.
With just 20 minutes a day, you’ll boost your metabolism, strengthen your muscles, and improve your cardiovascular health—all with exercises you can easily do at home, no gym required!
Whether you’re new to S.I.T. or looking for a structured program that fits your busy schedule, this guide pairs with our video for a complete, step-by-step workout experience. Let’s get ready to crush those fitness goals together!

What is S.I.T. Training (Sprint Interval Training)?
Most likely, you already know all about S.I.T workouts, any why they are so great - after all that’s how you got here! But if you need a refresher, no worries! Sprint Interval Training (S.I.T.) is a game-changer, especially for women 40 and older. Unlike traditional cardio which requires you to grind away for long periods, S.I.T. is all about short, intense bursts of activity followed by lower-intensity recovery. It's fast and efficient, and the benefits are impressive.
Here’s the kicker: S.I.T. has been shown to boost metabolism, improve cardiovascular health, and torch fat faster than your typical workout. INTRODUCTION
Welcome to your Full Body S.I.T. Workout Guide!
This ebook is designed to be the perfect companion to our follow-along workout video, giving you everything you need to understand and master Sprint Interval Training (S.I.T.) right from your living room.
With just 20 minutes a day, you’ll boost your metabolism, strengthen your muscles, and improve your cardiovascular health—all with exercises you can easily do at home, no gym required!
Whether you’re new to S.I.T. or looking for a structured program that fits your busy schedule, this guide pairs with our video for a complete, step-by-step workout experience. Let’s get ready to crush those fitness goals together!
1
BENEFITS OF S.I.T",". STYLE WORKOUT
What is S.I.T. Training (Sprint Interval Training)?
Most likely, you already know all about S.I.T workouts, any why they are so great - after all that’s how you got here! But if you need a refresher, no worries! Sprint Interval Training (S.I.T.) is a game-changer, especially for women 40 and older. Unlike traditional cardio which requires you to grind away for long periods, S.I.T. is all about short, intense bursts of activity followed by lower-intensity recovery. It's fast and efficient, and the benefits are impressive.
Here’s the kicker: S.I.T. has been shown to boost metabolism, improve cardiovascular health, and torch fat faster than your typical workout. For women in their 40s, this kind of training helps to combat age-related muscle loss, supports joint health, and makes the most of your workout time—because let’s be real",", life’s busy! You can get your heart racing, feel energized, and walk away with a big sense of accomplishment in just 7 minutes. Sounds like a win-win, right?
This Ebook is a follow-along guide for your Bonus S.I.T workout, and is meant to help provide you with some extra insight and information so you can make the most of your routine!
2
WHAT YOU NEED FOR THIS WORKOUT
Note that this workout is longer than the traditional 7- minute workouts that you might find in the One & Done program, that’s because this is specially designed to push you a little harder! If you aren’t able to complete the intermediate/advanced workouts in the traditional One & Done Program, then I would suggest you start there before starting this!
If you’re ready to start then follow these steps! Get your video loaded on any smart device, whether your phone, iPad, or smart TV! Then all you’ll"," need is:
Water Yoga mat A watch or timer Light weights (if applicable)

30 seconds forward, Arm Circles 30 seconds backward

30 seconds clockwise, 30 Hip Circles seconds counterclockwise
Now, let's jump into the intervals!

INSTRUCTIONS FOR EACH EXERCISE
WARM-UP (3 MINUTES)
March in Place (30 seconds)
Stand tall with your arms relaxed at your sides. Begin lifting your knees one at a time as if you are marching. Swing your arms naturally in coordination with your legs. Keep a moderate pace to get your heart rate up, but don’t overexert yourself.
Arm Circles (30 seconds forward, 30 seconds backward)
Extend your arms out to the sides at shoulder height, keeping them straight. Begin making small circles with your arms, gradually increasing the size of the circles. For the first 30 seconds, rotate your arms forward. Then, reverse the direction for the next 30 seconds, circling your arms backward.
Bodyweight Squats (30 seconds)
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and toes slightly turned out. Lower your body into a"," squat by pushing your hips back and bending your knees, keeping your chest lifted and your weight in your heels. Return to standing by pressing through your heels and squeezing your glutes at the top. Repeat at a steady pace.
Hip Circles (30 seconds clockwise, 30 seconds counterclockwise)
Stand with your feet slightly wider than hip-width apart. Place your hands on your hips and make large, slow circles with your hips, keeping your upper body still. Rotate your hips in a clockwise direction for 30 seconds, then switch to counterclockwise for another 30 seconds.
13
INSTRUCTIONS FOR EACH EXERCISE
MAIN WORKOUT (16 MINUTES)
High Knees (30 seconds all-out sprint)
Stand with your feet hip-width apart. Begin running in place, driving your knees up as high as possible toward your chest. Pump your arms as you would when sprinting. Keep your core engaged and aim for a fast pace"," to raise your heart rate.
Active Recovery: March in place for 60 seconds, lifting your knees moderately high and moving at a relaxed pace.
Jump Squats (30 seconds)
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Lower into a squat position by bending your knees and pushing your hips back. Explode upward by jumping into the air, reaching your hands overhead. Land softly with your knees slightly bent, and immediately lower back into the squat position to repeat.
Active Recovery: Perform air squats for 60 seconds at a slow, controlled pace, lowering into a squat without jumping.
Mountain Climbers (30 seconds fast pace)
Start in a plank position with your hands directly under your shoulders and your body in a straight line from head to heels. Quickly alternate driving your knees toward your chest as if "climbing" in place. Keep your core tight and your hips low, moving at a fast pace.
Active Recovery: Stand up and slowly perform standing"," toe touches for 60 seconds. Reach down toward your toes while keeping your legs straight, alternating hands. 14
INSTRUCTIONS FOR EACH EXERCISE
MAIN WORKOUT (16 MINUTES)
Burpees (30 seconds, as many as you can)
Start standing with your feet shoulder-width apart. Drop into a squat position, place your hands on the ground, and jump your feet back into a plank position. Lower your chest to the ground in a push-up motion, then push back up. Jump your feet forward to your hands and explosively jump into the air, reaching your arms overhead. Repeat.
Active Recovery: Walk in place or step side to side for 60 seconds, moving at a slow and steady pace.
BURPEE MODIFICATION
Squat to Step Back (30 seconds, as many as you can)
Start in a standing position with feet shoulder-width apart. Perform a squat, lowering down as if sitting back into a chair",". As you rise from the squat, step one leg back into a reverse lunge, keeping your torso upright. Return to standing, then repeat with the other leg. Continue alternating legs.
Active Recovery: Walk in place or step side to side for 60 seconds, moving at a slow and steady pace.
15
INSTRUCTIONS FOR EACH EXERCISE
COOL-DOWN (1 MINUTE)
Standing Hamstring Stretch (30 seconds)
Stand with your feet together and hinge forward at your hips, reaching your hands toward your toes. Keep your legs straight but avoid locking your knees. Hold this position for 30 seconds, feeling the stretch along the back of your legs.
Child’s Pose on the Floor (30 seconds)
Kneel on the floor and sit back on your heels. Lower your torso toward the ground and stretch your arms forward, resting your forehead on the floor. Hold this position for 30 seconds, focusing on deep, calming breath","s.
